Certainly! Here's a step-by-step guide on how to use Hibernate to map the product entity to the product table in the Couchbase database:

1. Configure Couchbase and Hibernate:
   a. Set up Couchbase by installing and running the Couchbase server.
   b. Configure the Couchbase server to enable N1QL query support.
   c. Add the necessary Couchbase dependencies to your project's build.gradle or pom.xml file, such as the Couchbase Java SDK and Spring Data Couchbase.

2. Define the Product entity class:
   a. Create a new Java class called "Product" in your project's source code.
   b. Add necessary annotations to the class to indicate that it's an entity and specify the table name.
   For example:
   ```java
   import javax.persistence.Entity;
   import javax.persistence.Id;
   import javax.persistence.Table;

   @Entity
   @Table(name = "product")
   public class Product {
       @Id
       private String id;
       private String name;
       private String description;
       private double price;
       // other attributes, getters and setters
   }
   ```

3. Configure Couchbase connection and repositories:
   a. Create a new configuration class, e.g., "CouchbaseConfig", and annotate it with "@Configuration".
   b. Define a bean for the Couchbase connection by using the annotation "@Bean" and providing the necessary configuration properties.
   c. Create a CouchbaseRepository interface for the Product entity by extending the appropriate Spring Data Couchbase repository interface.

   For example:
   ```java
   import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Value;
   import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
   import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
   import org.springframework.data.couchbase.config.AbstractCouchbaseConfiguration;
   import org.springframework.data.couchbase.repository.config.EnableCouchbaseRepositories;

   @Configuration
   @EnableCouchbaseRepositories
   public class CouchbaseConfig extends AbstractCouchbaseConfiguration {

       @Value("${couchbase.cluster.bucket}")
       private String bucketName;

       @Value("${couchbase.cluster.password}")
       private String password;

       @Override
       protected List<String> getBootstrapHosts() {
           return Arrays.asList("localhost"); // replace with your Couchbase server host
       }

       @Override
       protected String getBucketName() {
           return bucketName;
       }

       @Override
       protected String getBucketPassword() {
           return password;
       }

       @Override
       public String typeKey() {
           return "javaClass"; // specify typeKey if using the Spring Data Couchbase version prior to 4.0
       }
   }
   ```

4. Test the mapping:
   a. Write a test case using JUnit or a similar testing framework to create a product object and save it to the Couchbase database.
   b. Verify that the product is successfully mapped and persisted in the product table.

   For example:
   ```java
   import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
   import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
   import org.springframework.boot.test.context.SpringBootTest;

   import static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;

   @SpringBootTest
   class ProductRepositoryTest {

       @Autowired
       private ProductRepository productRepository; // replace with your Couchbase repository

       @Test
       void testProductMapping() {
           Product product = new Product();
           product.setId("1");
           product.setName("Product 1");
           product.setDescription("Description 1");
           product.setPrice(9.99);
           // set other attributes

           Product savedProduct = productRepository.save(product);

           assertThat(savedProduct).isNotNull();
           assertThat(savedProduct.getId()).isEqualTo("1");
           assertThat(savedProduct.getName()).isEqualTo("Product 1");
           assertThat(savedProduct.getDescription()).isEqualTo("Description 1");
           assertThat(savedProduct.getPrice()).isEqualTo(9.99);
           // verify other attributes
       }
   }
   ```

