When using Hibernate to map entities to a database, such as Couchbase, you should use the `javax.persistence` annotations for defining the entity class and mapping its attributes. The `javax.persistence` package provides a set of standard annotations for Object-Relational Mapping (ORM) with Java.

The specific Couchbase-related annotations, such as `@Document` or `@Field` for Couchbase specific mapping, are not used when using Hibernate with Couchbase as the underlying persistence technology. Hibernate abstracts the database-specific details and provides a standard JPA-based approach for mapping entities.

So, in your entity class, you should continue using the `javax.persistence` annotations like `@Entity`, `@Id`, and `@Table` for defining the entity and its attributes. For example:

```java
import javax.persistence.Entity;
import javax.persistence.Id;
import javax.persistence.Table;

@Entity
@Table(name = "product")
public class Product {
    @Id
    private String id;

    private String name;
    private String description;
    private double price;
    // other attributes, getters and setters
}
```

These annotations will be recognized by Hibernate and used to create the appropriate mappings to the underlying Couchbase database.

Starting from Jakarta EE 9, the package `javax.persistence` has been moved to `jakarta.persistence`. If you are using a Jakarta EE version later than 9 or a corresponding framework like Jakarta Persistence, you should import `jakarta.persistence` instead of `javax.persistence`.

Here's how you can update the imports in your entity class:

```java
